1 3. a. A city that does not provide the report in a timely manner or in the correct format
2 is not eligible to receive a grant from the fund for a period of two years starting
3 from the date the report was due.
4 b. If a city uses the funding in a manner inconsistent with the requirements of this
5 section as identified in any financial audits conducted by the state auditor or an
6 independent accounting firm, the state treasurer shall reduce any future grants to
7 that city by the amount spent that was inconsistent with the requirements.
8 c. If a city adopts an ordinance or policy that interferes or conflicts with an energy
9 infrastructure project permitted or approved by a state agency, the city is not
10 eligible to receive any grants from the fund beginning on the later of the date on
11 which the city adopted the ordinance or policy, or the date on which the state
12 agency permits or approves the project.
13 2.4. Within forty days after the fund balance is greater than or equal to the amount needed
14 for the grants under this subsection or by September thirtieth of each odd-numbered
15 year, whichever is earlier, the state treasurer shall distribute moneys in the fund as
16 grants to cities for essential infrastructure projects. The state treasurer shall distribute
17 the grants only if the fund balance is at least ten percent of the amount needed for
18 distributions under this subsection based on the following:
19 a. Two million five hundred thousand dollars to each city with a population of at
20 least five thousand;
21 b. Five hundred thousand dollars to each city with a population of at least two
22 thousand but less than five thousand; and
23 c. One hundred twenty-five thousand dollars to each city with a population of at
24 least one thousand but less than two thousand.
25 d. If, at the time of the distributions, the moneys in the fund are less than the
26 amount needed for the grants under this subsection, the state treasurer shall
27 distribute the grants under this subsection on a pro rata basis.
28 e. For the purposes of determining the city's population under this subsection, the
29 state treasurer shall use the most recent actual or estimated census data
30 published by the United States census bureau.
